[FULL TEXT ANALYSIS BELOW]
GLP-1 weight loss drugs could help people with impulse control and
addiction disorders, say researchers
Elisabeth Mahase
Glucagon-likepeptide-1receptoragonists(GLP-1RAs),
used to treat diabetes and for weight loss, may be
linked with a reduced risk of substance use and
neurocognitive disorders, a US study in people with
type 2 diabetes found, but could also carry an
increased risk of gastrointestinal disorders and drug
induced pancreatitis.1
Researchers from the Veterans Affairs St Louis
Healthcare System in Missouri used US Department
of Veterans Affairs databases to follow 1.96 million
people with type 2 diabetes for a median period of
3.7 years and to map associations between GLP-1RA
use and 175 health outcomes.
The study, published in Nature Medicine, included
215 970 people who used a GLP-1RA, comparing these
with 159 465 people who used sulfonylureas, 117 989
who used dipeptidyl peptidase IV (DPP4) inhibitors,
258 614 who used sodium glucose cotransporter-2
(SGLT2) inhibitors, and 1.2 million who used (“usual
care”) any non-GLP-1RA antihyperglycaemic drug.
Participants were enrolled between October 2017 and
December 2023.
The researchers reported that, in comparison with
the usual care group, use of GLP-1RAs was associated
with a reduced risk of substance related disorders,
including alcohol (hazard ratio (HR) 0.89 (95%
confidence interval 0.86 to 0.92)), cannabis (0.88
(0.83 to 0.93)), stimulants (0.84 (0.78 to 0.91)) and
opioids (0.87 (0.82 to 0.92)).
GLP-1RA use was also linked to reduced risk of
suicidal ideation or attempt or intentional self-harm
(HR 0.90 (0.86 to 0.94)), schizophrenia and other
psychotic disorders (0.82 (0.76 to 0.89)), and
Alzheimer’s disease (0.88 (0.78 to 0.99)).
Other measures where GLP-1RAs were associated
with reduction in risk were coagulopathy and clotting
disorders (HR 0.92 (0.89 to 0.95)), pulmonary
hypertension (0.82 (0.78 to 0.85)), cardiac arrest (0.78
(0.71 to 0.85)), bacterial infections (0.88 (0.86 to
0.90)), pneumonia (0.84 (0.82 to 0.86)), and
inflammatory bowel disease (0.88 (0.82 to 0.94)).
However,theresearchersalsofoundseveraloutcomes
where GLP1-RAs were linked to increased risk,
including for drug induced acute pancreatitis (HR
2.46 (2.05 to 2.96)), nausea and vomiting (1.30 (1.26
to 1.33)), gastroesophageal reflux disease (1.14 (1.12
to 1.16)), non-infectious gastroenteritis (1.12 (1.08 to
1.18)), sleep disturbances (1.12 (1.10 to 1.14)), and
arthritis (1.11 (1.09 to 1.13)).
The researchers did not measure the absolute risk for
the 175 health outcomes but have said that their
follow-on work from this study will do so. They also
noted other limitations to their study, including that
the population they were studying—US
veterans—mainly comprised older white men, which
limited applicability of their findings to the general
population, because the health effects of these drugs
“may vary across age, race, ethnicity, and sex.”
Mechanisms of action
Ziyad Al-Aly, assistant professor of medicine at
Washington University School of Medicine and chief
of the research and education service at the VA Saint
Louis Healthcare System, suggested two possible
mechanisms to explain the possible wide ranging
effects of GLP-1RAs. Speaking at a Nature briefing on
the paper, Al-Aly said, “One mechanism is that
obesity itself is really bad for health. Obesity itself
increases the risk of heart problems and kidney
problems and increases risk of infections and clotting
and all of that. And when treating obesity effectively
by using GLP-1 receptor agonists you see beneficial
effects that are beyond a reduction in BMI or weight
loss.
He continued, “The second potential pathway is that
there are GLP-1 receptors throughout the body,
including in the brain, and they act to suppress
centres of the brain that are involved in impulse
control and reward signalling. By doing so, you can
actually explain why these drugs may also reduce
the risk of addiction disorders, like alcohol use
disorders, cannabis use disorders, opioid use
disorders etc,” adding that there was a school of
thought that obesity itself could be caused by a food
addiction disorder.
GLP-1 receptors also have a “stabilising effect” on
the endothelial cells that line the blood vessels,
meaning these drugs could have “potential effects
on the heart,” while research indicated that they
could “reduce the propensity for clot formation and
inflammation, including neuroinflammation,” Al-Aly
said. “We tend to think of drugs as surgically
designed to do only one thing, but the reality is it’s
almost never like that.”
Al-Aly also emphasised the importance of
understanding the risks. “There are beneficial effects,
but these drugs are not without risks. For example,
acute pancreatitis could actually land people in the
hospital or result in death. So it’s very, very important
to note that these medications are not without side
effects.”
1
Xie Y, Choi T, Al-Aly Z. Mapping the effectiveness and risks of GLP-1
receptor agonists. Nat Med 2025. doi: 10.1038/s41591-024-03412-w.
